~ sasha.add_openness(-1)
"The Tower is a rough card, but change can be good," you say. "Sometimes things need to fall apart before they can—"

"Stop," Sasha says. "I need you to say the thing. Not the gentle version. The *thing.*"

You opened the door and found them with no bracelet, wrinkled flannel, shaking hands. They didn't come here for 'change can be good.'

"...I'm sorry."

"It's okay. Just — try harder on the next one. Please."

+ [Swallow the rebuke and reach for the last card] -> Sasha.Session2.Position2.End

# --- Position 2 Convergence ---

:: Sasha.Session2.Position2.End
Two cards on the cloth now. Where You Are. What's Real.

@if sasha.openness >= 4:
    Sasha is very still. Not the fragile stillness of Session 1 — this is the stillness of someone who has finished pretending. They know what the cards are saying. They probably knew before they sat down. But hearing it spoken aloud, in this room, with the cards laid out like evidence — it's become undeniable.

    "Last card," they say. Steady.
@elif sasha.openness >= 1:
    Something has clarified. Sasha is looking at the cards the way you look at a map when you've been driving lost for hours and finally see the 'YOU ARE HERE' dot.

    "Last card."
@else:
    Sasha shifts in their chair. The reading hasn't hit the way either of you hoped. But they're still here.

    "Last one," you say.
@endif

+ [Turn the last card] -> Sasha.Session2.Position3Hub

# ============================================================================
# POSITION 3: WHERE THIS GOES
# ============================================================================

:: Sasha.Session2.Position3Hub
@render render_reading(reading=reading)

**Position 3: Where This Goes — The Trajectory**

**{cards[2].get_display_name()}**

@if cards[2].name == "Death":
    Death. Not literal death — transformation. A skeleton rides a white horse through a field where figures kneel, fall, and surrender. The old world ending. The new one not yet visible.

    @if cards[2].reversed:
        Reversed: the transformation is resisted. You're clinging to the old version of yourself even as it dies.
    @endif

    Sasha looks at the card for a long time.

    "Death," they say.

    "Transformation," you correct. Gently. {cards[2].reversed ? "But reversed — you're fighting it. Holding onto the thing that's already gone." | "The old version of this story is ending, Sasha. Whether you choose it or not. The trajectory is already in motion."}

    -> Sasha.Session2.Position3.Death

@else:
    The Star. A figure kneels by water, pouring from two vessels under a sky full of stars. Hope. Healing. The quiet after the storm.

    @if cards[2].reversed:
        Reversed: the hope is there but you can't access it. You've been hurt too long to believe in gentleness.
    @endif

    Sasha's breath catches. After the Devil or the Ten of Wands, after the Ten of Swords or the Tower — The Star.

    "That's the card from last time," they say. "The pretty one."

    {cards[2].reversed ? "\"Reversed. The hope is there, Sasha. But you've stopped believing in it.\"" | "\"The Star. In 'Where This Goes.' This is the trajectory, Sasha. After all of this — this is what's ahead of you.\""}

    -> Sasha.Session2.Position3.Star
@endif

# --- Death ---

