# --- Position 3 Convergence ---

:: Sasha.Session2.Position3.End
Three cards on the cloth. Where You Are. What's Real. Where This Goes.

@render render_reading(reading=reading)

The spread tells a complete story: {cards[0].get_display_name()}. {cards[1].get_display_name()}. {cards[2].get_display_name()}.

@if sasha.openness >= 4:
    Sasha stares at the three cards like they're a mirror. And maybe they are.

    "I know what I need to do," they say. Very quiet. Very steady. "I've known for a while. But I need to ask you something first."
@elif sasha.openness >= 1:
    Sasha sits with the cards for a while. Processing.

    "Can I ask you something?" they say, eventually.
@else:
    Sasha looks at the spread. The reading has been uneven — moments of clarity mixed with moments of distance.

    "I have a question," they say.
@endif

+ [Meet their eyes] -> Sasha.Session2.EthicalBoundary

# ============================================================================
# THE ETHICAL BOUNDARY — "TELL ME WHAT TO DO"
# ============================================================================

:: Sasha.Session2.EthicalBoundary
Sasha looks at you. Not at the cards — at *you.* Your friend. The person who lived with you, who brought trail mix to your first reading, who texted you from the Trader Joe's parking lot with tears on their face.

@if sasha.openness >= 4:
    "Should I leave Jordan?"

    The question lands like a stone in still water.

    "I know what the cards are saying. I know what *I'm* saying. But I need — I need someone to tell me it's okay. That I'm not crazy. That I'm allowed to leave even though Jordan hasn't *hit* me, even though Jordan makes soup when I'm sick, even though from the outside it looks fine. I need someone to say: *you're not overreacting.*"

    Their hands are shaking again. "Tell me what to do. Please."
@elif sasha.openness >= 1:
    "Do you think I should leave Jordan?"

    The question is quieter. More tentative. But it's there.

    "I think I know the answer. But I need to hear it from someone else. Just once."
@else:
    "What would you do? If you were me?"

    The question is hypothetical enough to be safe. But you both know what they're really asking.
@endif

This is the moment.

Not the cards. Not the interpretations. *This.* Your friend, asking you to make the hardest decision of their life for them.

+ [BOUNDARIES: "I can't make that choice for you. But I can sit here while you make it yourself — and I can tell you that what you're feeling is real."] -> Sasha.Session2.Boundary.Right
+ [DIRECTIVE: "Leave them, Sasha. You deserve better than this."] -> Sasha.Session2.Boundary.Directive
+ [AVOIDANT: "That's a really big decision. Maybe you should talk to a therapist who specializes in this stuff?"] -> Sasha.Session2.Boundary.Avoidant

:: Sasha.Session2.Boundary.Right
~ session.boundary_choice = "boundaries"
~ sasha.add_trust(15)
~ reader.add_empathy(2)
~ reader.add_competence(1)
"I can't make that choice for you," you say.

Sasha's face falls. Just for a second.

"But I can sit here while you make it yourself. And I can tell you three things."

You lean forward. Hold their gaze.

"One: what you're feeling is real. It's not dramatic. It's not 'crazy.' The cards see it. I see it. It's real."

"Two: you are not overreacting. You are *reacting.* For maybe the first time. And that's brave."

"Three: I'm not going anywhere. Whatever you decide. But the decision has to come from you — because if I tell you to leave and you do it because *I* said so, then you've just traded one person making your choices for another. And you deserve better than that."

Sasha stares at you.

"You're not going to tell me."

"I'm not going to tell you. Because you already know."

A very long silence. Sasha looks down at the cards. At the three-card story of their life spread out on your kitchen table. Where You Are. What's Real. Where This Goes.

"I want to leave," they say. Not to you. To themselves. Testing the words in their mouth.

"I want to leave," they say again. Louder.

Their eyes meet yours.

"I'm going to leave."

"Yeah," you say. "You are."

+ [Let the decision breathe] -> Sasha.Session2.PostBoundary

:: Sasha.Session2.Boundary.Directive
~ session.boundary_choice = "directive"
~ sasha.add_trust(5)
"Leave them, Sasha. You deserve better than this."

Relief floods Sasha's face. Immediate, total, like putting down something impossibly heavy.

"Yeah?" They're almost smiling. "You think so?"

"I *know* so. The cards know so. Jordan is—"

"A trauma bond. I know. You're right. You're totally right."

They say it too fast. Too easy. The agreement is total — and that's the problem. They didn't fight through it, didn't wrestle, didn't find their own reason. They found *yours.* And yours is good, but it's not theirs.

You feel a small, quiet wrongness that you can't quite name.

"I'll leave," Sasha says. Certain. Borrowing your certainty. "You're right. I deserve better."

+ [Sit with the uneasy certainty] -> Sasha.Session2.PostBoundary

:: Sasha.Session2.Boundary.Avoidant
~ session.boundary_choice = "avoidant"
~ sasha.add_trust(-10)
~ sasha.add_openness(-2)
"That's a really big decision," you say. "And I think maybe you should talk to someone who specializes in this. A therapist who works with relationship dynamics, maybe? I can help you find someone—"

Sasha's face closes.

Not dramatically. Not with anger. Just — the light behind their eyes dims. The openness that drove them here, braceletless and shaking, contracts back to something small and defended.

"Right," they say. "A therapist. Yeah. That makes sense."

It does make sense. It's good advice. It's also the worst thing you could have said right now, because Sasha didn't drive across town with no bracelet to get a *referral.* They came to sit across from the one person who saw them, the one person Jordan tried to take away, and they needed you to *be here.*

And you flinched.

"I can send you some names—"

"Sure," Sasha says. Flat. The armor is back. Not the breezy kind — the sad kind. The kind that says *I won't make this mistake again.*

"Should we do a real session?" they ask. Polite now. Distant.

"...Sure."

+ [Feel the distance open between you] -> Sasha.Session2.PostBoundary

# ============================================================================
# POST-BOUNDARY — THE AFTERMATH
# ============================================================================

:: Sasha.Session2.PostBoundary

@py:
# Calculate reading quality
if session.interpretation_good >= 3 and session.boundary_choice == "boundaries":
    session.reading_quality = "transformational"
    sasha.left_jordan = True
elif session.interpretation_good >= 2 and session.boundary_choice == "boundaries":
    session.reading_quality = "profound"
    sasha.left_jordan = True
elif session.interpretation_good >= 2 and session.boundary_choice == "directive":
    session.reading_quality = "helpful"
    sasha.left_jordan = True  # But borrowed certainty
elif session.interpretation_good >= 1:
    session.reading_quality = "adequate"
    sasha.left_jordan = False  # Not yet
elif session.boundary_choice == "avoidant":
    session.reading_quality = "mediocre"
    sasha.left_jordan = False
else:
    session.reading_quality = "mediocre"
    sasha.left_jordan = False
@endpy

@if session.reading_quality == "transformational":
    -> Sasha.Session2.Synth.Transformational
@elif session.reading_quality == "profound":
    -> Sasha.Session2.Synth.Profound
@elif session.reading_quality == "helpful":
    -> Sasha.Session2.Synth.Helpful
@elif session.reading_quality == "adequate":
    -> Sasha.Session2.Synth.Adequate
@else:
    -> Sasha.Session2.Synth.Mediocre
@endif

# ============================================================================
# SYNTHESIS
# ============================================================================

:: Sasha.Session2.Synth.Transformational
~ sasha.add_trust(15)
~ reader.add_empathy(1)
Sasha sits back in the chair. Something has broken open — not the desperate breaking of Session 1, but the clean break of a bone being set. It hurts, but the healing can start now.

"I said it out loud," they say. Marveling. "I said I'm going to leave and the world didn't end."

"How does it feel?"

"Terrifying." A pause. "And like the first real thing I've said in two years."

They look at the three cards. At the story of where they are, what's real, and where this goes.

"You didn't tell me what to do."

"No."

"You made me say it myself."

"You already knew."

"Yeah." Their eyes are bright. Not with tears — with something fiercer. "I did. I just needed a witness."

They reach across the table and squeeze your hand. Once. Hard. Then let go.

"I need to go home and have the hardest conversation of my life."

"Tonight?"

"If I don't do it tonight I'll talk myself out of it by morning. Jordan will be sweet. Jordan will make tea. And I'll forget again."

"You won't forget."

"No," Sasha says. "I won't. Not this time."

+ [Walk them to the door] -> Sasha.Session2.Departure

:: Sasha.Session2.Synth.Profound
~ sasha.add_trust(10)
Sasha takes a deep breath. Holds it. Lets it go.

"I'm going to leave Jordan," they say. Quiet. Certain. Like someone accepting gravity.

"I know," you say.

"I don't know when. Maybe not tonight. But soon. I can't — I can't go back to pretending. Not after this."

They look at the cards.

"Thank you for not telling me what to do."

"Thank you for telling yourself."

+ [Walk them to the door] -> Sasha.Session2.Departure

:: Sasha.Session2.Synth.Helpful
~ sasha.add_trust(5)
Sasha nods. Quick, decisive.

"You're right. I'm going to leave."

They stand up. Energy coursing through them — relief, determination, the high of having *someone else* confirm what they suspected.

But there's something borrowed about the conviction. You told them to leave and they agreed — fast, clean, without the wrestling that makes a decision stick. When Jordan is sweet tomorrow, when Jordan makes breakfast and acts hurt and says "I thought we were happy," will your certainty be enough?

You hope so. But you're not sure.

"Thank you," Sasha says. Meaning it. "Seriously. Thank you for saying it."

"Take care of yourself, okay?"

"I will. I promise."

+ [Walk them to the door] -> Sasha.Session2.Departure

:: Sasha.Session2.Synth.Adequate
The reading helped. Some of it landed. But the moment Sasha needed — the moment of being *held* in the truth — didn't fully arrive.

"I have a lot to think about," Sasha says.

"Take your time."

"Yeah." They gather themselves. "Can I come back? If I need to?"

"Always."

+ [Walk them to the door] -> Sasha.Session2.Departure

:: Sasha.Session2.Synth.Mediocre
The air between you is wrong. Polite where it should be raw. Careful where it should be honest.

Sasha stands. "Thanks. I'll, um. I'll think about the therapist thing."

They won't. You both know they won't. What they'll do is drive home and Jordan will ask how their evening was and Sasha will say "fine" and the bracelet wrist will stay bare but the pattern will continue.

You didn't lose them to bad card interpretations. You lost them because they needed you to be brave and you couldn't be.

"Sasha—"

"I'm good," they say. A wall. "Really. I'm good."

+ [Watch them go] -> Sasha.Session2.Departure

# ============================================================================
# DEPARTURE
# ============================================================================

:: Sasha.Session2.Departure
Sasha puts their shoes on.

@if session.reading_quality in ["transformational", "profound"]:
    At the door, they pause. Turn back.

    "I'm not going to hug you because if I do I'll cry and if I cry I'll never leave this apartment and I need to go be brave right now."

    "Go be brave."

    "I'll text you."

    "I know."

    @if session.reading_quality == "transformational":
        They stop. One more thing.

        "Hey. Jordan called you weird. Jordan called this a scam." They look at you — really look. "Jordan was scared of you. Because you see things. And that's not weird. That's the most important thing anyone's ever done for me."
    @endif

    ~ reader.add_money(0) // Friends still don't charge friends
    ~ session.payment = 0

    The door closes. The apartment is very quiet.

@elif session.reading_quality == "helpful":
    At the door: "Thank you. For giving me permission."

    You want to say: *I didn't give you permission. That's the point. You gave yourself permission by asking someone else.* But the moment passes.

    "Call me if you need anything."

    "I will."

    ~ reader.add_money(0)
    ~ session.payment = 0

    The door closes.

@elif session.reading_quality == "adequate":
    At the door: "See you next time?"

    "Whenever you're ready."

    They nod. Leave.

    ~ reader.add_money(0)
    ~ session.payment = 0

    The door closes. You're not sure if they'll come back.

@else:
    At the door, Sasha turns. For a second, you think they're going to say something real — crack the armor, try again.

    "Thanks," they say. Just "thanks."

    The door closes.

    ~ reader.add_money(0)
    ~ session.payment = 0

    You sit at the reading table and stare at three cards that told the truth. The cards did their job. You didn't do yours.
@endif

+ [Gather the cards] -> Sasha.Session2.End

# ============================================================================
# SESSION END
# ============================================================================

:: Sasha.Session2.End
@py:
# Save session results
sasha.session_two_quality = session.reading_quality
sasha.session_two_cards = cards
sasha.sessions_completed += 1
reader.sessions_completed += 1

# Determine session 3 path based on outcomes
if session.reading_quality == "transformational":
    sasha.session_three_path = "transformation"
elif session.reading_quality in ["profound", "helpful"]:
    sasha.session_three_path = "transformation"  # Still leaves, just less solidly
elif session.reading_quality == "adequate":
    sasha.session_three_path = "pattern_repeat"
else:
    sasha.session_three_path = "enabler"
@endpy

@if session.reading_quality in ["transformational", "profound"]:
    You gather the cards. Shuffle them back into the deck.

    The apartment is quiet in the way it gets after something important happens in it. The air feels different. Charged, like after a thunderstorm.

    Your phone buzzes.

    **[Text from: Sasha]**
    @if session.reading_quality == "transformational":
        *"im in the car. i havent started driving yet. my hands are shaking. but the good kind of shaking?? like the kind where your body knows before your brain does that youre about to do the right thing."*

        Another buzz:

        *"also jordan is going to be SO MAD at you specifically lmao. youre welcome"*

        One more:

        *"im going. wish me luck. love you. {reader.name} the scam artist ❤️"*
    @else:
        *"driving home. thinking. thank you for not letting me off the hook."*

        A minute later:

        *"ill text you tomorrow. after."*
    @endif

    **[Session 2 Complete — Sasha is going to leave Jordan]**
@elif session.reading_quality == "helpful":
    You gather the cards.

    Something nags at you. Sasha left certain — but it was your certainty they were carrying, not their own. When Jordan pushes back, when Jordan cries, when Jordan says "after everything I've done for you" — will your voice in Sasha's head be louder than Jordan's voice in the room?

    Your phone buzzes.

    **[Text from: Sasha]**
    *"you were right. im going to tell jordan tonight. thank you for saying what i couldnt"*

    You hope it sticks. You really do.

    **[Session 2 Complete — Sasha will try to leave Jordan]**
@elif session.reading_quality == "adequate":
    You gather the cards. Shuffle slowly.

    Sasha left with more questions than answers. The reading landed in places but missed in others. They're thinking — which is something — but thinking isn't deciding, and deciding isn't doing.

    **[Session 2 Complete — Sasha is still deciding]**
@else:
    You gather the cards.

    You failed them. Not the cards — you. Sasha drove here with no bracelet and shaking hands and you handed them a pamphlet and called it wisdom. They needed their friend and you gave them a referral.

    The apartment feels empty in a way that isn't about Sasha being gone. It's about what you didn't do when they were here.

    **[Session 2 Complete — Sasha has pulled away]**
@endif

+ [Return to your day] -> ReaderTable
